  "What is the 'butterfly effect'?": "",
  "The concept that small perturbations in initial conditions can lead to vastly different outcomes in chaotic systems, placing inherent limits on weather prediction": "",
  "The migration pattern of butterflies that follows weather systems as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "The observation that butterflies cause storms, particularly regarding metaphorically under normal circumstances": "",
  "A computer bug that causes weather models to fail in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "The butterfly effect, coined by meteorologist Edward Lorenz, illustrates that in chaotic systems like the atmosphere, even tiny differences in starting conditions (metaphorically, a butterfly flapping its wings) can lead to dramatically different outcomes over time, fundamentally limiting long-range weather prediction.": "",
  "What is data assimilation in weather forecasting?": "",
  "Converting weather data into graphical maps": "",
  "The process of deleting old weather data from databases": "",
  "Storing weather data in long-term archives": "",
  "The process of combining observations with model predictions to create the best possible estimate of current atmospheric conditions": "",
  "Data assimilation is a mathematical technique that combines millions of observations (from radiosondes, satellites, radar, aircraft, and surface stations) with a short-range model forecast to produce the best possible estimate of current atmospheric conditions, which then serves as the starting point for new forecasts.": "",
  "What is nowcasting?": "",
  "Very short-range forecasting (0 to 6 hours) that relies heavily on current radar and satellite observations": "",
  "A technique for predicting yesterday's weather retroactively": "",
  "Long-range climate prediction extending decades into the future": "",
  "Historical weather analysis of past events": "",
  "Nowcasting focuses on very short-range forecasts from 0 to 6 hours ahead, relying heavily on extrapolating current radar and satellite observations forward in time rather than relying on NWP models, and is especially useful for predicting thunderstorm development and movement.": "",
